{"id":"1912.03281","submitter":"Ali Teimouri Dr","authors":"Thomas M. A. Fink, Ali Teimouri","title":"The mathematical structure of innovation","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Despite our familiarity with specific technologies, the origin of new\ntechnologies remains mysterious. Are new technologies made from scratch, or are\nthey built up recursively from new combinations of existing technologies? To\nanswer this, we introduce a simple model of recursive innovation in which\ntechnologies are made up of components and combinations of components can be\nturned into new components---a process we call technological recursion. We\nderive a formula for the extent to which technological recursion increases or\ndecreases the likelihood of making new technologies. We test our predictions on\nhistorical data from three domains and find that technologies are not built up\nfrom scratch, but are the result of new combinations of existing technologies.\nThis suggests a dynamical process by which known technologies were made and a\nstrategy for accelerating the discovery of new ones.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 6 Dec 2019 18:25:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-09"}
