{"id":"1912.03355","submitter":"Javad Najafi","authors":"Javad Najafi, Florian Altegoer, Gert Bange, and Christian Wagner","title":"Swimming of bacterium \\textit{Bacillus subtilis} with multiple bundles\n  of flagella","comments":"7 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":"Soft matter 2019","doi":"10.1039/C9SM01790A","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.bio-ph cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We characterize the bundle properties for three different strains of\n\\textit{B. subtilis} bacteria with various numbers of flagella. Our study\nreveals that, surprisingly, the number of bundles is independent of the number\nof flagella, and the formation of three bundles is always the most frequent\ncase. We assume that this relates to the fact that different mutants have the\nsame body length. There is no significant difference between the bundle width\nand length for distinct strains, but the projected angle between the bundles\nincreases with the flagellar number. Furthermore, we find that the swimming\nspeed is anti-correlated with the projected angle between the bundles, and the\nwobbling angle between the swimming direction and cell body increases with the\nnumber of flagella. Our findings highlight the impact of geometrical properties\nof bacteria such as body length and bundle configuration on their motility.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 6 Dec 2019 22:05:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-10"}
